## 🏗️ II. The Book of Blueprints (The Dockerfile)

A raw, single-stage Dockerfile is a sin of gluttony. It ships the compiler, the SDK, and the source code into production. 

To achieve salvation, you must use **Multi-Stage Builds**. This pattern uses a heavy image to build the code, but copies only the compiled, final binary into a tiny, secure runtime image.

```dockerfile
# ---------------------------------------------------
# STAGE 1: THE FORGE (Build Environment)
# ---------------------------------------------------
FROM mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/sdk:8.0 AS build-env
WORKDIR /App

# Cache the restoration of dependencies
COPY *.csproj ./
RUN dotnet restore

# Copy the remaining source code and compile the binary
COPY . ./
RUN dotnet publish -c Release -o out

# ---------------------------------------------------
# STAGE 2: THE SANCTUARY (Runtime Environment)
# ---------------------------------------------------
# Notice we use the 'aspnet' runtime, NOT the 'sdk'. 
# It is 80% smaller and contains no compilers.
FROM mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/aspnet:8.0
WORKDIR /App

# Pull only the compiled artifacts from 'The Forge'
COPY --from=build-env /App/out .

# Document the port this container listens on internally
EXPOSE 8080

# The absolute command executed when the container breathes life
ENTRYPOINT ["dotnet", "MyApi.dll"]
```

